BSSD At-Home Art Club added 14 new photos to the album: Ephemera.
April 23 at 1:40 PM 路

Ephemera: here only for a day; here one moment and gone the next.

Ephemeral art celebrates change. Rather than trying to create something that lasts forever, artist that work with ephemera want to create something for now, this moment, this place.

post_text:
Ephemera: Lasting only a momement, a day.

Ephemeral art is often created using the arrangement of materials in their natural environment. Over time, these materials erode, fall apart, or are rearranged so the artwork is reabsorbed into the world around.

See full lesson plan: https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/1keAk4tLgMcxXA9djVCSXWrWe0L70QSxHSB_CIGxmyEs/edit?usp=sharing

post_text:
For this painting, I took advantage of some ways the coffee moves differently than watercolor. Instead of layering translucently to show previous layers, new coffee reactivates any existing pigment on the page, often allowing later layers to remove previously painted lines.

See lesson Plan here: https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/1qLSX4IbQYJcRGa4tHc5mvPBlQPYnr8zdStN6xjouDms/edit?usp=sharing

April 13 at 2:36 PM 路

Brew a pot of coffee and feel free to drink most of it.

Set a small portion aside to use as an ink/paint.

Use same/day coffee for light/warm brown. Or let your coffee evaporate and then add just a few drops or teaspoon of water to make dark/cool brown.

post_text:
This is a week I've been really looking forward to. The Coffee Challenge. Make a piece of artwork using coffee as your medium!

Since households may not have paintbrushes, in my lesson plan we making calligraphy using a fork as a quill.

To make the ink, simply brew some coffee and set a small amount aside in a bowl or on a small plate. Fresh coffee tends to give a warm, orange hued in while aged/evaporated coffee (with a few drops of water added) can be used for a darker brown.

Lesson Plan: https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/1qLSX4IbQYJcRGa4tHc5mvPBlQPYnr8zdStN6xjouDms/edit?usp=sharing

This week we are seashells. My example is specifically bivalve filter feeders (like clams, oysters, and mussels) that get their energy by consuming organisms like the plankton we drew last week!

If you don't have any shells in the house, you could try using the photo page in the lesson plan attached as a drawing reference.

Lesson plan: https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/15bHv7qowhupfM2YFja4xf25oKd5scAlALDYaFqfOS0E/edit?usp=sharing

post_text:
This week we are drawing plankton, small organisms that float or drift on water currents. They can be found in streams, rivers, lakes, and oceans of ecosystems worldwide.

Here is a resource I found with great plankton information and images: https://coast.noaa.gov/data/estuaries/pdf/planet-plankton-plankton-identification.pdf

I am also attaching the lesson plan I wrote for a drawing project: https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/1ySAHpeEu86w3nOSAHcXsUehFGAcTRdfzbvhPjXdDFek/edit?usp=sharing
